Today is the anniversary of the passing of the great Rabbi Elimelech of Lizhensk who I’m 9th generation descendant. 

Here’s a beautiful line from a prayer he composed, “Put into our hearts that everyone should see the qualities of their fellows, and not their faults.” 

Known as the “Rebbe of Rebbes”
He and his brother, Rebbe Zusha of Anipoli, were devoted students of the Maggid of Mezrich, who led the Chassidic movement after the passing of the Baal Shem Tov.

To this day, thousands visit his gravesite in Lizhensk, Poland, especially today on his yahrtzeit, Adar 21 
May his memory be a blessing 🕯️

During our trip to Newport, one of the highlights was visiting the oldest synagogue in America, the Touro Synagogue. Built in 1763, the community dates back to the 1600s. In the second picture, you can see a 500 year-old Torah. The third picture shows a getaway escape door, which wasn't actually necessary for Newport, but was built in support of European synagogues that all had them and needed them at the time. It was fascinating to learn about the rich history of this beautiful synagogue and how it has stood the test of time. Highly recommend a visit if you're ever in the area!

As an Orthodox Jew, @rabbitailor has a long beard and covers his hair with a yarmulke and hat. But he also dresses differently than other religious Jewish men, who typically opt for white shirts and black suit jackets. Instead, he wears colorful clothing with interesting patterns, and sometimes completes his look with the perfect pair of suspenders.

“People are seeing someone religious doing something completely different,” he said. “It’s really special.”

When Rabbi Yosel Tiefenbrun was 28, he and his family moved back to Brooklyn, where he was born, and he opened up his own tailoring house, @tiefenbrunnyc, in East Williamsburg. 

He quickly became a huge success, serving international clients and being featured in the New York Times, Fortune Magazine, GQ, the New York Post, and Time Out London. He also created suits for the show Madam Secretary.

Read more about his story on aish.com

Today is Tisha B'Av the saddest day for the Jewish people. It's a solemn time of mourning and remembrance, commemorating the destruction of our sacred First and Second Temples in Jerusalem. The First Temple, built by King Solomon, was destroyed by the Babylonians in 586 BCE, and the Romans destroyed the Second Temple in 70 CE.

This day reminds us not only of the physical loss of our holy sites but also the exile and displacement of our people from our homeland. Throughout history, we've faced many tragedies, like the expulsion from Spain in 1492 and the horrors of the Holocaust. On Tisha B'Av, we fast, pray, and reflect, mourning the loss of our Temples and the suffering of our ancestors. Yet, despite these hardships, this day also highlights our strong resilience and determination to preserve our faith and heritage. For all those observing have an easy and meaningful rest of your fast 🙏

Tonight marks the start of the holiest day on the Jewish calendar, Yom Kippur. On this day, we transcend our physical bodily needs and instead direct our attention towards our spiritual and pure essence. We abstain from eating and drinking, allowing us to fully concentrate on returning to our spiritual roots.

To symbolize purity and emulate angels, we don a white Kittel. This garment also serves as a reminder of our mortality and the importance of repentance, as it bears a resemblance to a burial shroud. Wearing the Kittel on Yom Kippur humbles our hearts, prompting us to reflect on our imperfections and the need for forgiveness. 

Gmar Chatima Tova, meaning a good final sealing, is a traditional blessing exchanged during this time, signifying our hopes for a positive outcome and a meaningful year ahead. 

Wishing you an easy and meaningful fast and may we all be inscribed and sealed in the book of life for a happy, healthy and prosperous year ahead. 🙏🙏

Let me remind you of what Mark Twain wrote in 1899 for Harper’s when anti-Semitism was widespread in the United States.

“If the statistics are right, the Jews constitute but one percent of the human race. It suggests a nebulous dim puff of stardust lost in the blaze of the Milky Way.
Properly the Jew ought hardly to be heard of, but he is heard of, has always been heard of.
He is as prominent on the planet as any other people and his commercial importance is extravagantly out of proportion to the smallness of his bulk.

His contributions to the world's list of great names in literature, science, art, music, finance, medicine, and obtuse learning are also way out of proportion to the weakness of his numbers.

He has made a marvelous fight in this world in all the ages and has done it with his hands tied behind him.
He could be vain of himself and be excused for it. The Egyptians, the Babylonians and the Persians rose, filled the planet with sound and splendor, and faded to dream stuff and passed away.

The Greeks and the Romans followed and made a vast noise and they are gone.

Other peoples have sprung up and held their torch high for a time. But it burned out, and they sit in twilight now or have vanished.

The Jew saw them all. Beat them all, and is now what he always was, exhibiting no decadence, no infirmities of age, no weakening of his parts, no slowing of his energies, no dulling of his alert and aggressive mind. All things are mortal but the Jew. All other forces pass, but he remains.” 

May we all have a true Shabbat SHALOM 🕊️

Earlier today lighting the 1st candle of Chanukah at the atelier. In this climate the more Menorahs lit the better. 

The story of Chanukah takes us back to Jerusalem in the 2nd century BCE, a time when Jews had our holy temple and the Seleucid Greek empire ruled over us. In 168 BCE, King Antiochus IV Epiphanes banned Jewish practices and defiled our beloved Temple by placing an altar to Zeus Olympios and sacrificing pigs.

But the Maccabees, against all odds, bravely fought back and emerged triumphant against the Greeks. When they finally reached the temple, they discovered only a small amount of pure oil, enough for just one night. However, a miraculous event occurred—the oil miraculously lasted for a miraculous eight nights.

Like many Jewish holidays, Chanukah reminds us of the struggles we’ve faced throughout history. We’ve endured countless attempts to annihilate us, yet with the help of God, we’ve always emerged victorious.

This Chanukah, more than ever, as we light the menorah, we remember our fellow Jews who have been kidnapped in Gaza, our brave soldiers on the battlefield, and the countless lives that have been lost. We’re thinking about the crazy rise in anti semitism on college campuses and in the streets of capitals worldwide. In the midst of these challenges, let us fervently pray and hope for peace. May the radiant glow of the candles illuminate not only our homes but also the world around us, bringing much-needed light, solace, and unity. 

Happy Chanukah!! Light the menorah wherever you are 🕎
